<assessment id="u3_m3_normal2_lbd_tutor1">
   <title>Tutor</title>
   <question id="q1">
      <body>
         <p>(a) Place the flags
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100809-0500"?>1<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100808-0500" content="one"?>
            standard deviation on either side of the mean. What is the area between these two
            values? What does the standard deviation rule say this area is?</p>
         <p>(b) Repeat for
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100823-0500"?>2<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100822-0500" content="two"?>
            and
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100826-0500"?>3<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100825-0500" content="three"?>
            standard deviations on either side of the mean. Again compare the standard deviation
            rule with the area given in the applet.</p>
      </body>
      <short_answer id="A"/>
      <part>
         <response input="A" match="*" score="1"/>
         <explanation>
            <p>(a) According to the
               applet<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100836-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
               the exact probability that a normal random variable will get a value that is within 1
               standard deviation of its mean is
               .6826<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100845-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
               which is pretty close to what the
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100849-0500"?>S<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100849-0500" content="s"?>tandard
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100854-0500"?>D<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100853-0500" content="d"?>eviation
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100857-0500"?>R<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100856-0500" content="r"?>ule
               tells us (.68).</p>
            <p>(b) According to the applet, the exact
               probabilit<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100909-0500"?>y<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100908-0500" content="ies"?>
               that a normal random variable will get a value that is within 2 standard deviations
               of its mean is .9544,
               which<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100918-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
               again, is pretty close to what the
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100923-0500"?>S<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100922-0500" content="s"?>tandard
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100926-0500"?>D<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100926-0500" content="d"?>eviation
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100929-0500"?>R<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100929-0500" content="r"?>ule
               tells us (.95).</p>
            <p>Also, according to the applet, the exact probability that a normal random variable
               will get a value that is within 3 standard deviations of its mean is .9974, which is
               very close to what the
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100953-0500"?>S<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100953-0500" content="s"?>tandard
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100956-0500"?>D<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100956-0500" content="d"?>eviation
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100959-0500"?>R<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T100958-0500" content="r"?>ule
               tells us (.997).</p>
            <p>We conclude that the
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T101005-0500"?>S<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T101005-0500" content="s"?>tandard
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T101007-0500"?>D<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T101007-0500" content="d"?>eviation
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T101010-0500"?>R<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T101010-0500" content="r"?>ule
               is very accurate.</p>
         </explanation>
      </part>
   </question>
